**Abstract:**
A detailed essay dated May 22, 1993, titled "Reflecting on Frei's Project," summarizing and analyzing Hans Frei's "The Eclipse of Biblical Narrative." The document explains Frei's argument that large portions of the Bible belong to the genre of "realistic narrative" in which meaning cannot be conveyed otherwise than by the narrative itself, and that this distinctive meaning was lost in the eighteenth century. It traces Frei's account of the three elements of traditional realistic interpretation (literal-historical reading, figural/typological unity, and incorporation of reader into the biblical world) and their breakdown, with the separation of literal from historical meaning and the confusion of history-likeness with history.

**AI Recommendation:** Excellent summary and analysis of Frei's work; essential for understanding how the author appropriates Frei for the Chantilly project.

